# Writing & Editing Project Documentation

Read this before making changes to any `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `docs/ai/` file, or skill.

## Core Principle: LLMs Have an Instruction Budget

LLMs reliably follow ~150-200 instructions, with degradation beyond that. The agent's system prompt already consumes ~50. Every line in root `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` competes for attention. Less is more.

## The Three-Layer Architecture

This project uses a layered documentation system that's **agent-agnostic** - works with any coding agent that supports `AGENTS.md` (the emerging universal standard).

### Layer 1: Root Files (Always Loaded)

- **`AGENTS.md`** - The primary root file. Universal rules only. Keep under 100 lines.
  - Read by: Codex, Cursor, Windsurf, Aider (natively), Claude Code (as fallback)
- **`CLAUDE.md`** - *Optional*. Only create if you have Claude Code-specific content (commands, hooks, etc.) that shouldn't live in `AGENTS.md`. If it exists, it duplicates the universal rules + adds the Claude-specific bits.
  - Read by: Claude Code (primary)
- **`.github/copilot-instructions.md`** - *Optional*. Copy the root `AGENTS.md` reference table here if you use GitHub Copilot.

### Layer 2: Skills + Nested AGENTS.md (Auto-Activated)

- **`.agents/skills/*/SKILL.md`** - Shared skills. Thin pointers that tell the agent to read the relevant `docs/ai/` file. Auto-activated based on `description` matching.
  - Claude Code accesses these via a symlink at `.claude/skills/`.
  - Codex reads `.agents/skills/` directly.
- **Nested `AGENTS.md`** in source directories - Auto-injected by agents when editing files in those directories. Used for non-negotiable guardrails in high-stakes directories.

### Layer 3: Reference Docs (Loaded On-Demand)

- **`docs/ai/*.md`** - Agent-agnostic detailed guidelines. The source of truth. Skills and nested AGENTS.md point here. Humans read these directly.

## Where to Put New Instructions

| The instruction... | Put it in... |
|---|---|
| Always matters, regardless of task | Root `AGENTS.md` |
| Claude Code-specific (hooks, `/command` names) | Root `CLAUDE.md` only |
| Only matters for a specific topic | `docs/ai/` reference doc |
| Is a non-negotiable rule for a specific directory | Nested `AGENTS.md` in that directory |
| Needs to auto-activate for agents | `.agents/skills/` SKILL.md (points to docs/ai/ file) |
| Is a one-off fix or edge case | Nowhere. Don't add it. |

## Rules for Editing

### Root AGENTS.md
- Target: under 100 lines
- Every instruction must pass: "Does this matter for ANY task?" If not, move it out.
- Reference table is intent-based ("Working on X | Read Y"), not feature-based
- Agent-agnostic wording - no assumptions about which specific agent is running

### Root CLAUDE.md (optional)
- Only exists if you have Claude-specific content (commands, hooks, Claude Code configuration)
- Mirrors AGENTS.md universal rules for discoverability, then adds Claude-specific sections
- If kept thin, can just point to `AGENTS.md`

### docs/ai/ Reference Docs
- One doc per topic area, not per feature
- Every file starts with the "already loaded" banner (see template below)
- Keep cross-references correct (if you rename a file, update all pointers)
- Don't duplicate content across docs. One canonical location per concept.
- Update `docs/ai/README.md` file table when adding/removing docs

#### Banner format

Every `docs/ai/` file must start with this banner so the agent doesn't re-read it within a session:

```markdown
> **IMPORTANT: Before reading, check if you already read this file earlier in this session. If yes, skip the read and announce "Context already loaded: <filename>.md (re-using from earlier)". If no, read it and announce "Context loaded: <filename>.md".**
```

#### Diagrams with Mermaid

Prefer mermaid diagrams over prose for:
- System architecture (component boxes + arrows)
- Sequence flows (request lifecycle, event propagation)
- State machines (form dirty/clean, cache states)

**Why:** Agents read diagrams faster than paragraphs describing the same shape. A 15-line mermaid block often replaces 200 words of prose.

**Where:** Inline inside the relevant `docs/ai/` file, not as separate `.mermaid` files. Keep the diagram next to the prose that explains it.

Use fenced code blocks with the `mermaid` language tag:

```` markdown
```mermaid
graph LR
    Browser --> API[Next.js API]
    API --> Prisma
    Prisma --> DB[(Supabase Postgres)]
```
````

Both GitHub and VS Code render mermaid natively.

### .agents/skills/ SKILL.md Files
- Keep them thin - just a description and a pointer to docs/ai/
- The `description` field is the activation trigger. Write it with specific keywords (file paths, library names, user-facing actions).
- A skill can be both user-invocable (`/<skill-name>`) and auto-invoked
- Claude Code accesses these via symlink at `.claude/skills/`; Codex reads `.agents/skills/` directly
- Both agents use the same SKILL.md format (name, description frontmatter + body)

### Nested AGENTS.md Files
- Keep under 10 lines. These are guardrails, not documentation.
- State the rule and why. Don't explain background.
- Point to docs/ai/ for details
- Only create if the directory has non-negotiable rules
- Any agent that supports `AGENTS.md` reads these (Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, etc.)

## Anti-Patterns

- **Stuffing everything in root files.** The more you add, the less gets followed.
- **Duplicating content across files.** One canonical location. Others point to it.
- **Adding stale content.** Delete, don't accumulate.
- **Example code in docs.** It duplicates the codebase and goes stale. Use `file:line` pointers.
- **Using docs for linting rules.** Linters are cheaper, faster, and deterministic.
- **Auto-generating docs.** Every line should be manually crafted.
- **Claude-specific content in AGENTS.md.** If it's Claude-only (hook names, `/command` specifics), put it in `CLAUDE.md` instead so other agents don't get confused.

## Maintenance

### Keep the indexes in sync

When adding, removing, or renaming a `docs/ai/` file, you **must** update all indexes that point to it:

1. **`AGENTS.md` reference table** at the project root
2. **`CLAUDE.md` reference table** at the project root (if it exists)
3. **`.agents/skills/` SKILL.md files** - any skill that points to this doc (update description + body)
4. **Nested `AGENTS.md` files** - any "Read before editing:" pointers in source directories
5. **`docs/ai/README.md` file table** - the catalog
6. This file's "Current File Inventory" section below (if you maintain one)

### Other maintenance

- When creating new source directories, check if they need a nested AGENTS.md and/or a new skill
- Periodically prune skills with descriptions that never trigger - they're dead weight in the registry

